      <bioghist id="aspace_4897d3e09b616d8c0615473236a55ac0">
         <head>Edward Killoran Brown (1905-1951)</head>
         <p>Edward Killoran Brown, Canadian professor and literary critic. He published under the name E. K. Brown. Brown wrote several non-fiction books, including his posthumously published biography <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>Willa Cather: A Critical Biography</part>
            </title> (1953). After Brown's death, LeonEdel, American literary critic and biographer, assisted in publishing the biography.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <bioghist id="aspace_eb0fdb816b0160d137b6c5d514beb082">
         <head>Willa Cather (1873-1847)</head>
         <p>Willa Seibert Cather, American author. Her novels include <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>O Pioneers!</part>
            </title>, <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>My Ántonia</part>
            </title>, and <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>The Song of the Lark</part>
            </title>. In 1923 she was awarded the Pulitzer Prize for <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>One of Ours</part>
            </title>.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_b1dd82e896964ca42301a659bbb3ca46">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The collection documents Edward Killoran Brown's research and writing of the biography of American author Willa Cather, <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>Willa Cather: A Critical Biography</part>
            </title>. The collection contains correspondence, writings, and research notes. Correspondence includes original letters to Cather from various individuals. The material was compiled by Brown in the course of his work on Cather.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <arrangement id="aspace_5327a8a2e925102fa318cf8eddb32360">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>Organized into two series: I. Correspondence, 1874-1950. II. Writings, 1947-1953.</p>  
      </arrangement>
